2) Evaluation against the two candidates:
- Reprise‑era anthology: The cited features — close‑mic, intimate vocal‑forward mixes; tasteful analog remaster that preserves natural dynamics; restrained low end; sparse piano and warm late‑night orchestration; concise sequencing and preserved analog character — align very closely with my stated preferences (intimacy, low‑compression/natural dynamics, front‑and‑center vocals, tasteful piano/organ, restrained low end, and sequencing that rewards front‑to‑back listening).
- Styx Greatest Hits: Its features — arena‑ready theatrical rock, glossy multi‑tracked guitars, stacked harmonies, punchy tight drums, polished synths and piano‑forward moments, and a driving rhythmic foundation — contain some AOR elements I like (hooks, piano moments, strong mastering), but they lean heavily toward bombastic, arena‑scale production, glossy multi‑tracking and stacked, theatrical presentation. Those are precisely the traits I indicated I dislike when they sacrifice intimacy and produce overblown, singles‑first bombast.
