- Tradeoffs outweigh positives: Although the compilation offers tight multi‑part harmonies (a plus), the combination of glossy sheen, gated drums, and decisive mastering represents several of my stated dislikes. Those are larger conflicts with my core priorities (analogue warmth, low compression, vocal micro‑detail) than the anthology’s minor mismatch (the anthology is guitar‑centric and has a centered lead rather than an off‑center lead).
Overall assessment:
The Bill Withers anthology aligns more closely with my core priorities — preserved transient snap, restrained compression, analogue warmth, vocal immediacy, crisp transients and cohesive sequencing — whereas the Singles‑first compilation conflicts with several non‑negotiable dislikes (glossy sheen, gated drums, heavy mastering). For those reasons I select the Bill Withers anthology.

